 at the height of the empire's power, territorial reach, and global influence. As a high-caste Hindu who worked for a series of Muslim monarchs and other officials, forming powerful friendships along the way, Chandar Bhan's experience bears vivid testimony to the pluralistic atmosphere of the Mughal court, particularly during the reign of Shah Jahan, the celebrated builder of the Taj Mahal. But his widely circulated and emulated works also touch on a range of topics central to our understanding of the court's literary, mystical, administrative, and ethical cultures, while his letters and autobiographical writings provide tantalizing examples of early modern Indo-Persian modes of self-fashioning. Chandar Bhan's oeuvre is a valuable window onto a crucial, though surprisingly neglected, period of Mughal cultural and political history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthors, IndiczMogul EmpirevBiography. 0aPersian literaturezIndiaxHistory and criticism. 0aSecretarieszMogul EmpirevBiography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aakbar.  aasia.  aaurangzeb alamgir.  abiography.  abrahman.  acaste.  achandar bhan.  aclassics.  acourtier.  acultural history.  agreat mughals.  ahindu.  ahinduism.  ahistory.  aidentity.  aindia.  aindopersian.  aislam.  ajahangir.  aliterature.  amiddle eastern.  amughal court.  amughal.  amunshi.  amuslim monarchs.  anonfiction.  apersian poets.  apolitical history.  areligious identity.  areligious pluralism.  areligious tolerance.  aroyal court.  aself fashioning.  ashah jahan.  asouth asia.  ataj mahal.  aworld li